Introduction

What is our topic?

We are interested in analyzing the trends in bachelors degrees conferred to undergraduate students by postsecondary institutions across the United States during the 2010-11 to 2022-23 academic years.

What question(s) are we trying to answer with our analysis?

  1. What are the trends in bachelor's degrees granted to undergraduate students?
  2. Is Computer Science the trend, meaning is it the most popular field of study among undergraduate students?
  3. Is Computer Science a popular field of study among women in comparison to men?

Why is answering those questions important?

Based on our time at the University of Maryland, Computer Science and other STEM-related subjects appear to have become in demand among students in recent years. The demand has increased so much that certain majors like Computer Science have become limited enrollment programs. We want to analyze the data to determine whether this is true across the United States and consider what could be the reason behind this trend.

Data Curation

The dataset for our project is sourced from the U.S. Department of Education, National Center for Education Statistics, Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System (IPEDS), Completions component. The dataset is about the completion of degrees by undergraduate students across the United States during the academic years 2010-11 to 2022-23. The data includes the title of the degrees, the total number of degrees conferred for each title, the number of degrees conferred to women and men for each title, and the academic year.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Our first objective is to see the trends in fields of study, more specifically in Computer Science, by analyzing the dataset. If we look at the University of Maryland in recent years, Computer Science has become such a popular program among undergraduates that it has become a limited enrollment program. We want to see if this is true across the nation.

In our exploratory data analysis, we will do the following statistical tests:

  1. Hypothesis Test with ANOVA: Test whether or not Computer Science is the most popular field of study among others.
  2. Pearson and Spearman Correlation: Test for correlation between Computer Science and other programs.
  3. Hypothesis Test with T-Test: The tech field is mainly dominated by men. We want to test whether Computer Science is the most popular field of study among women or men.

Since there are many fields of study, we will only focus on those that are a good representation of the general subjects for our exploratory analysis.

Statistical Method #1: Hypothesis Testing with ANOVA

We will use the Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) test to determine if there is a signifcant difference between Computer Science and the other fields of study. To understand more about how, when, and why to use ANOVA, here is a comprehensive guide.

ANOVA Test

The null and alternate hypotheses:

  • HO: The average value for the number of degrees conferred by postsecondary institutions is the same for all fields of study.
  • HA: The average value for the number of degrees conferred is different for at least one field of study.
In[]:
# perform the ANOVA test
from scipy.stats import f_oneway
res = f_oneway(computer_sciences["Total"], biological_sciences["Total"], education["Total"], engineering["Total"], humanities["Total"], mathematics["Total"], psychology["Total"], social_sciences["Total"], visual_arts["Total"], health_professions["Total"], business["Total"])
res.pvalue
Out[]:
np.float64(9.483985319843573e-122)

Conclusion From ANOVA Test

Reject the null hypothesis, because the p-value, 9.48e-122, is less than the significance level, 0.05. Which concludes that there is significant difference among the fields of study. However, we do not know which one. So we will do post-hoc analysis to see which one. More specifically, we care about the difference between Computer Sciences and the other fields.

In[]:
# perform the post-hoc analysis
from scipy.stats import tukey_hsd
result = tukey_hsd(computer_sciences["Total"], biological_sciences["Total"], education["Total"], engineering["Total"], humanities["Total"], mathematics["Total"], psychology["Total"], social_sciences["Total"], visual_arts["Total"], health_professions["Total"], business["Total"])
print(result)

Conclusion From Post-Hoc Analysis

  • In the result, 0 is Computer Sciences, 1 is Biological Sciences, 2 is Education, 3 is Engineering, 4 is Humanities, 5 is Mathematics, 6 is Psychology, 7 is Social Sciences, 8 is Visual Arts, 9 is Health Professions, and 10 is Business.
  • For Computer Sciences, the p-value is less than the significane level, 0.05, in comparision to Biological Sciences, Education, Humanities, Mathematics, Visual Arts, Health Professions, and Business but greater in comparison to Engineering, Psychology, and Social Sciences.
  • In conclusion, Computer Sciences is not significantly different from all fields but some. Therefore, Computer Sciences is not the most popular field of study but another one is.

Statistical Method #2: Pearson and Spearman Correlation Tests

Although we have concluded Computer Sciences is not the most popular field of study, we now want to test if there is a correlation between Computer Sciences and other fields of study to determine if there has been any growth or decline in assoication with other fields. The Pearson and Spearman correlation tests are useful here since they are used to measure the relationship between variables. After applying the test on two variables, a positive result implies a positive correlation and a negative result implies a negative correlation. In addition, the further away the result is from 0 (i.e. 1 or -1) the stronger the correlation and vice versa.

In[]:

Statistical Method #3: Hypothesis Testing with T-Test

T-Tests

We will conclude our exploratory analysis with another hypothesis testing with t-test to understand the role of gender in the fields of study, more specifically Computer Sciences. We are using t-test to compare the means of each group which will allow us to determine if there is a difference in the number of degrees conferred to men and women.

The null and alternate hypotheses:

  • HO: There is no difference in the number of degrees conferred to women and men by postsecondary institutions in various fields of study.
  • HA: The is a difference in the number of degrees conferred to women and men by postsecondary institutions in various fields of study.
In[]:
from scipy import stats

# ttest for computer sciences
res = stats.ttest_ind(computer_sciences["Women"], computer_sciences["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Computer Sciences, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# ttest for biological sciences
res = stats.ttest_ind(biological_sciences["Women"], biological_sciences["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Biological Sciences, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# ttest for education
res = stats.ttest_ind(education["Women"], education["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Education, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# ttest for engineering
res = stats.ttest_ind(engineering["Women"], engineering["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Engineering, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# ttest for humanities
res = stats.ttest_ind(humanities["Women"], humanities["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Humanities, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# test for mathematics
res = stats.ttest_ind(mathematics["Women"], mathematics["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Mathematics, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# ttest for psychology
res = stats.ttest_ind(psychology["Women"], psychology["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Psychology, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# ttest for social sciences
res = stats.ttest_ind(social_sciences["Women"], social_sciences["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Social Sciences, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# ttest for visual arts
res = stats.ttest_ind(visual_arts["Women"], visual_arts["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Visual Arts, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# ttest for health professions
res = stats.ttest_ind(health_professions["Women"], health_professions["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Health Professions, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

# ttest for business
res = stats.ttest_ind(business["Women"], business["Men"])
print(f"Field of Study: Business, p-value: {res.pvalue}")

Conclusion From T-Tests

Reject the null hypothesis, because the p-value for all fields of study including Computer Sciences is less than the significance level, 0.05, which concludes that the number of degrees conferred to men and women is significantly different.

Primary Analysis

Based on the results from our exploration, we will now use K-Means clustering as our machine learning technique. We will perform clustering on the total number of degrees conferred to students by postsecondary institutions to group each field of study by its popularity. From our exploratory data analysis, even though we know Computer Science is not the most popular program, we now want to know where it stands among other programs.

In this analysis, we will consider all the fields of study unlike the selected few chosen for the exploratory analysis.

In[]:
# apply the elbow method to determine the number of clusters
state = 42
inertias = []
K = range(1, 10)

for k in K:
    # apply kmeans clustering
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=state)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    inertias.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# plot the result to see the optimal number
plt.plot(K, inertias, marker="o")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("Inertia")
plt.title("Elbow Method for Optimal Number of Clusters")
plt.show()

The optimal number of clusters appear to be 2.

In[]:
# use the KElbowVisualizer from the yellowbrick library to verify result
from yellowbrick.cluster import SilhouetteVisualizer
from yellowbrick.cluster import KElbowVisualizer
model = KMeans(random_state=state)
visualizer = KElbowVisualizer(model, k=K)
visualizer.fit(X)
visualizer.show()

X["Cluster"] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

We will now visualize the results from K-Means clustering to gain insights. Since there is only one feature used in the analysis, total number of degrees, a strip plot and a bar chart are effective visualizations for the result.

Strip Plot Interpretations

  • There is a clear divide between the two clusters.
  • Data points that are not popular are clustered to the far left, shown as blue dots and labeled as 0.
  • Data points that are popular are clustered to the far right, show as green dots and labeled as 1.
  • Majority of the data points are in Cluster 0, the not popular cluster, while only 3 observable data points are in Cluster 1, the popular cluster.

  • Computer Sciences is near the top of the not popular cluster. It is the second highest, right below Education.

Insights and Conclusions

The goal of our project was to analyze the trends in bachelors degrees conferred to undergraduate students by postsecondary institutions across the United States with the emphasis on Computer Science. We wanted to share the trends with uninformed readers and either confirm their theories or share new findings with informed readers. Regarding Computer Science, we wanted to answer questions like is Computer Science the most popular field of study among undergraduate students? Is Computer Science a popular field of study among women in comparison to men? We wanted to answer those questions because based on our time at the University of Maryland, Computer Science has become the most popular choice of major among students in recent years. The demand has increased so much that it has become a limited enrollment program. We wanted to analyze the data to determine whether this is true across the United States and consider what could be the reason behind this trend.


Our exploratory data analysis showed us that Computer Science is not the most post popular field of study among students across the United States as indicated by the online media. Instead, the popular choices are programs related to health professions, business, liberal arts and humanities, etc. However, based on our correlation tests, we confirmed that there is growth in Computer Science in correlation to some other fields. Even among women, it is not a popular field of study in comparison to men. However, based on our t-test analysis and visualizations, we confirmed that there is an upward trend. While currently there is a big difference, women are interested in studying Computer Science. Our primary analysis with K-Means clustering basically confirmed the results from the exploratory analysis. The top three pouplar fields are programs related to health professions, business, and liberal arts and humanities. However, in the not popular cluster, Computer Science is second in its popularity.
